Introduction¶

A person makes a doctor appointment, receives all the instructions and no-show. Who to blame?
Here, we will analyze and explore a dataset that contains 100k medical appointments in Brazil, where a number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row.
And after that, come up with possible conclusions as to why so many patients do not show up to their appointment.

# Create bar graph function with 2 variables
"""
    Creates a bar graph with two bars, to visually compare two values
    Args:
        (str) label1 - Label of the first bar (x coordinates)
        (str) label2 - Label of the second bar (x coordinates)
        (int or float) height1 - Height of the first bar
        (int or float) height2 - Height of the second bar
        (str) color1 - Color/hex code of the first bar, default is blue
        (str) color2 - Color/hex code of the first bar, default is red
        (str) title - Title of the graph, default is 'Title'
        (str) xlabel - X label of the graph, default is 'xlabel'
        (str) ylabel - Y label of the graph, default is 'ylabel'
    Returns:
        Bar graph with two bars
    """
def bargraph(label1, label2, height1, height2, color1='b', color2='r', title='Title', xlabel='xlabel', ylabel='ylabel'):
    sns.set()
    fig = plt.figure(figsize =(7, 4))
    plt.bar(label1, height1, label=label1, color=color1)
    plt.bar(label2, height2, label=label2, color=color2)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

Data Dictionary¶

  • 01 - PatientId: Identification of a patient

Data Dictionary¶

  • 01 - PatientId: Identification of a patient
  • 02 - AppointmentID: Identification of each appointment
  • 03 - Gender: Male or Female. Female is the greater proportion, woman takes way more care of they health in comparison to man.
  • 04 - ScheduledDay: The day someone called or registered the appointment, this is before appointment of course.
  • 05 - AppointmentDay: The day of the actual appointment, when they have to visit the doctor.
  • 06 - Age: How old the patient is.
  • 07 - Neighbourhood: Where the appointment takes place.
  • 08 - Scholarship: True of False.
    Indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Famlia.
  • 09 - Hipertension: True or False
    If the patient has hypertension or not.
  • 10 - Diabetes: True or False
    If the patient has diabetes or not.
  • 11 - Alcoholism: True or False
    If the patient is an alcoholic or not.
  • 12 - Handcap: True or False
    If the patient is handicapped or not.
  • 13 - SMS_received: True or False
    If the patient received an SMS for the appointment or not.
  • 14 - No-show: No if the patient showed up to their appointment, and Yes if they did not show up.

In [32]:
# Convert `Neighbourhood` values from all caps to title
df['Neighbourhood'] = df['Neighbourhood'].str.title()
In [33]:
# Delete the row in `Age` that has a negative age
df.drop(df[df['Age']== -1].index[0], inplace=True)
In [34]:
# Since `AppointmentDay` has no time specified (all 00:00:00)
# Keep only the dates for both `AppointmentDay` and `ScheduledDay`
df['AppointmentDay'] = df['AppointmentDay'].str[:-10]
df['ScheduledDay'] = df['ScheduledDay'].str[:-10]
In [35]:
# Convert `AppointmentDay` and `ScheduledDay` column types to datetime 
df['AppointmentDay'] = pd.to_datetime(df['AppointmentDay'])
df['ScheduledDay'] = pd.to_datetime(df['ScheduledDay'])
In [36]:
# Create a column with the number of days between the day the patient scheduled and the appointment
df['Days'] = df['AppointmentDay'] - df['ScheduledDay']

We can see that patients that schedule their appointment to be on the same day that they called to schedule almost always show up.

Number of days between scheduling and appointment

If the patient scheduled 10 days or less before the appointment, they are most likely to show up.

In [51]:

show_mean = show_df['Days'].mean()
noshow_mean = noshow_df['Days'].mean()

bargraph('Showed up', 'Didn\'t show up', show_mean, noshow_mean, color1='#68a5ac', color2='#396469', 
         title='Mean of number of days between scheduling and appointment', 
         xlabel='Showed up/Didn\'t show up', ylabel='No. of days')

We can see that the average count of number of days between scheduling and appointment is higher for patients that did not show up.

Research Question 2:
Which features (Gender, Diabetes, Alcoholism, Handcap, Hypertension, Scholarship) are related to whether the patient will show up or not?:

  • Gender
  • Diabetes
  • Alcoholism
  • Handcap
  • Hypertension
  • Scholarship

1. Which gender is more likely to not show up?¶

In [52]:
# Number of males and females that did not show up
female = noshow_df['Gender'].value_counts()[0]
male = noshow_df['Gender'].value_counts()[1]
In [53]:
sns.set()
fig = plt.figure(figsize =(10, 7))
plt.pie([female, male], labels = ['Females','Males'], colors=['#C06C84','#355C7D'])
plt.legend()
plt.title("Proportion of male and female patients that did not show up")
plt.show()

It is clear that the number of patients that did not show up are mostly females, but could this be because there are more females in the dataset?

In [54]:
# Plot the total number of males and females
total_m = df['Gender'].value_counts()[1]
total_f = df['Gender'].value_counts()[0]

bargraph('Female', 'Male', total_f, total_m, color1='#C06C84', color2='#355C7D', 
         title='Total number of male and female patients', 
         xlabel='Gender', ylabel='No. of patients')

The number of females in the dataset is almost two times more than males, which means female patients are more likely to make an appointment.
However, the gender needs to be ratioed in order to make a fair comparison to find out which one is more likely to not show up.

In [55]:
# Ratio of males and females that didn't show
# eg. no. of females that didn't show / total no. of females
female_ratio = female/total_f
male_ratio = male/total_m

# Plot the graphs
sns.set()
plt.figure(figsize=(13,5))
plt.subplot(121)
pie = plt.pie([female_ratio*100, male_ratio*100], labels = ['Females','Males'], colors=['#C06C84','#355C7D'])
plt.legend()
plt.title("Proportion of male and female patients that did not show up")

# create second subplot on the right (1 row, 2 columns, position 2)
sns.set()
plt.subplot(122)
bar1 = plt.bar('Female', female_ratio, color='#C06C84', label='Female')
bar2 = plt.bar('Male', male_ratio, color='#355C7D', label='Male')
plt.title("Male and female patients that did not show up")
plt.xlabel("Gender")
plt.ylabel("Proportion of patients")
plt.legend()

plt.subplots_adjust(left=0.001, 
                    right=1, 
                    top=1, 
                    wspace=0.4, 
                    hspace=0.4)
plt.show()

Wow the first graph before the ratio was definitely deceiving!
We can now see that the number of male and female patients that did not show up are pretty much the same.
Therefore, gender is not one of the factors which determine if the patient will show up or not.

Used this for help to put the graphs side by side: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/56298327/how-to-scale-a-pie-chart-and-bar-chart-to-both-display

Most of the patients did not receive an SMS.

In [83]:
# Patients that received an SMS and showed up

# Patients that received an SMS but did not show up
noshow_received = noshow_df['SMS_received'].value_counts()[1]
In [84]:
labels = ['Received SMS']
showed = show_received
notshowed = noshow_received
width = 0.1 

sns.set()
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
fig.set_size_inches(10, 8)
ax.bar(labels, notshowed, width, label='Didn\'t show up', color='#FBDE44FF')
ax.bar(labels, showed, width, bottom=notshowed, label='Showed up', color='#F65058FF')

ax.set_ylabel('No. of patients')
ax.set_title('Number of patients that received an SMS')
ax.legend()

plt.show()

We can definitely see that if the patient receives an SMS, they are more likely to show up to the appointment.

Conclusions¶

  • In general, if a patient has a health condition, such as diabetes, hypertension or are handicapped, they are more likely to show up to the appointment. Alcoholic patients and patients that are enrolled in a welfare program are expected to show up to their appointments as well.

  • The proportion of male and female patients that did not show up are pretty much the same. Therefore, gender is not one of the factors which determine if the patient will show up or not.

  • Patients that call to schedule an appointment on the same day tend to show up, as well as if the patient scheduled 10 days or less before the appointment.
    The average number of days between scheduling and appointment is higher for patients that did not show up

  • People aged 65+ show up to the appointments the most.
    People aged 6-17 show up to the appointments the least.
    Ranking the age groups, from most likely to least likely to show up to appointments:
    • 65+
    • 0-5 and 35-64 are almost the same
    • 18-34
    • 6-17

  • Most patients scheduled an appointment for Tuesday, and very very few scheduled for Saturday.
    This is most likely because Saturday is in the weekend.
    Patients that have an appointment on Saturday are most likely going to show up.
    Other than that, we cannot really determine if a patient will show up to an appointment or not based on the other days of the week.

  • Most of the patients did not receive an SMS.
    However, if the patient receives an SMS, they are more likely to show up to the appointment.
    Healthcare centers should pay more attention to sending out an SMS to patients.

Limitations¶

  • There was no time given for the appointment day, which could have been a great factor to determining whether a patient will show up or not.
  • There were some records where the date of the appointment was before the schedule date.
